<subSubSection pageId="37" pageNumber="36" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="37.[192,1440,213,274]" pageId="37" pageNumber="36">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[192,316,213,239]" pageId="37" pageNumber="36">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Specimens of this species are superficially very similar to those of 
<taxonomicName box="[1040,1179,214,240]" class="Insecta" family="Cleridae" genus="Axina" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="37" pageNumber="36" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="conspicua">
<emphasis box="[1040,1059,214,240]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="36">A</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[1071,1179,215,240]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="36">conspicua</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. But, in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Opitz" authorityYear="2020" box="[1268,1369,214,240]" class="Insecta" family="Cleridae" genus="Axina" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="37" pageNumber="36" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ignota">
<emphasis box="[1268,1287,214,240]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="36">A</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[1300,1369,215,240]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="36">ignota</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
specimens the edges of the phallic plates are serrate; they are smooth in specimens of 
<taxonomicName box="[1087,1226,248,274]" class="Insecta" family="Cleridae" genus="Axina" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="37" pageNumber="36" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="conspicua">
<emphasis box="[1087,1106,248,274]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="36">A</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[1118,1226,248,273]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="36">conspicua</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="37" pageNumber="36" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="37.[191,1440,289,554]" pageId="37" pageNumber="36">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[192,338,289,315]" pageId="37" pageNumber="36">Description.</emphasis>
<emphasis box="[344,387,290,316]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="36">Size</emphasis>
. Length 11.0 mm; width 
<quantity box="[668,757,290,316]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.3" pageId="37" pageNumber="36" unit="mm" value="2.3">2.3 mm</quantity>
. 
<emphasis box="[767,826,290,315]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="36">Form</emphasis>
. As in 
<figureCitation box="[903,994,290,316]" captionStart="Figures 114–117" captionStartId="69.[192,279,1859,1885]" captionTargetBox="[192,1440,213,1828]" captionTargetId="figure-10@69.[192,1440,213,1828]" captionTargetPageId="69" captionText="Figures 114–117. Habitus of Axina species. 114) Axina conspicua. 115) A. equestris. 116) A. ignota. 117) A. ordinis." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4565039" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4565039/files/figure.png" pageId="37" pageNumber="36">Fig. 116</figureCitation>
. 
<emphasis box="[1004,1065,290,316]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="36">Color</emphasis>
. Cranium, thorax, and legs castaneous, except basal region of femora testaceous; antenna testaceous; elytra bicolorous, mostly testaceous, humeral angle and region near mesoscutellum black, disc infuscated at middle and near elytral apex; abdomen testaceous. 
<emphasis box="[191,250,391,417]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="36">Head</emphasis>
. Cranium finely punctate, frons slightly wider than length of antennal pedicel; EW/FW 50/18. 
<emphasis box="[1299,1377,391,417]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="36">Thorax</emphasis>
. Pronotum finely punctate, with 2 tumescences, concave at middle; PW/PL 110/170; elytra, asetiferous punctures not striate, punctures extend to elytral posterior 3/4, interstitial spaces very wide; EL/EW 440/80. 
<emphasis box="[1241,1345,459,485]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="36">Abdomen</emphasis>
. Female pygidium lunate, with transverse medial stalk (
<figureCitation box="[713,792,493,520]" captionStart="Figures 60–61" captionStartId="52.[192,279,1159,1185]" captionTargetBox="[192,1440,726,1129]" captionTargetId="figure-57@52.[192,1440,726,1129]" captionTargetPageId="52" captionText="Figures 60–61. Female genitalia. 60) Axina ignota. 61) A. latilinea." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4564991" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4564991/files/figure.png" pageId="37" pageNumber="36">Fig. 60</figureCitation>
); aedeagus (
<figureCitation box="[927,1006,493,520]" captionStart="Figures 25–28" captionStartId="48.[194,281,1152,1178]" captionTargetBox="[192,1440,719,1122]" captionTargetId="figure-65@48.[192,1440,719,1122]" captionTargetPageId="48" captionText="Figures 25–28. Aedeagi. 25) Axina bella. 26) A. ignota. 27) A. klisis. 28) A. luzia." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4564975" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4564975/files/figure.png" pageId="37" pageNumber="36">Fig. 26</figureCitation>
), phallobasic lobes very short, contiguous; edge of phallic plates serrate; phallobasic apodeme abbreviated.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="37.[192,857,569,596]" box="[192,857,569,596]" pageId="37" pageNumber="36">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[192,310,569,595]" pageId="37" pageNumber="36">Variation.</emphasis>
The available specimens are quite homogeneous.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="37.[192,979,611,638]" box="[192,979,611,638]" pageId="37" pageNumber="36">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[192,376,611,637]" pageId="37" pageNumber="36">Natural history.</emphasis>
Specimens were collected in 
<collectingCountry box="[702,767,611,637]" name="Brazil" pageId="37" pageNumber="36">Brazil</collectingCountry>
during November.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[192,970,653,680]" pageId="37" pageNumber="36" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="37.[192,970,653,680]" box="[192,970,653,680]" pageId="37" pageNumber="36">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[192,339,653,679]" pageId="37" pageNumber="36">Distribution</emphasis>
(for map see 
<figureCitation box="[490,568,653,679]" captionStart="Figure 72" captionStartId="57.[192,268,1867,1893]" captionTargetBox="[192,1440,213,1828]" captionTargetId="figure-10@57.[192,1440,213,1828]" captionTargetPageId="57" captionText="Figure 72. Distribution map for Axina species: A. analis, A. conspicua, A. equestris, A. ingnota, A. ordinis, A. trinalis, A. fortipes, A. furcula, A. megaspina, A. sexmaculata." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4565005" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4565005/files/figure.png" pageId="37" pageNumber="36">Fig. 72</figureCitation>
). This species is known from 
<collectingCountry box="[897,965,653,679]" name="Brazil" pageId="37" pageNumber="36">Brazil</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="37" pageNumber="36" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="37.[191,1440,695,755]" pageId="37" pageNumber="36">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[192,324,695,721]" pageId="37" pageNumber="36">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific epithet, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Opitz" authorityYear="2020" box="[554,623,696,721]" class="Insecta" family="Cleridae" genus="Axina" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="37" pageNumber="36" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ignota">
<emphasis box="[554,623,696,721]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="36">ignota</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, is a Latin name that stems from 
<emphasis box="[987,1067,696,721]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="36">ignotus</emphasis>
(= strange). I refer to the peculiar characteristic of the female pygidium.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
